{"type":"message","id":"6edb7eb8","parentId":"c68615cf","timestamp":"2026-05-09T09:46:04.417Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The cron_governor.py script itself runs fine and completes quickly. The issue is that the cron job (which runs as an isolated agentTurn) is timing out. The timeout is 60 seconds but the actual work takes only about 1 second.\n\nThe problem is that the isolated agent session (tina-reports) is slow to start up, not that the script is slow. The cron job payload launches an agentTurn in an isolated session, and that session needs to spin up, load context, etc.\n\nLet me look at the cron governor state file to understand what's happening.\n\nActually, looking at the job config again:\n\n\nThe agentId is set to \"tina-reports\" and the sessionKey points to the tina-reports session for Telegram. So when this isolated sessionTarget tries to launch, it's using the tina-reports agent configuration, which appears to be the bottleneck causing the timeout.\n\nLooking at other jobs with agentId \"tina-reports\" that are succeeding, they seem to work fine with similar session targets. But the cron governor jobs specifically are timing out at 60 seconds, while the same script runs in just 1 second locally. The issue might be in how the job message is formatted—it's calling a Python command directly, whereas the governor job might have a different message structure that's causing the delay.\n\nThe timeout was set to 60 seconds when the governor description was updated to mention \"每60分鐘系統監控（系統活動感知排程）— 20分鐘→60分鐘（降低系統負載）\", but the schedule is actually every 5 minutes. Even though the script completes in 1 second, the isolated agent session startup and tool call overhead is causing the timeout to trigger, which suggests the real bottleneck is in the agent's startup time, not the script execution itself. Let me check if there's something specific about how \"tina-reports\" is configured that's causing this. the isolated session to start, which takes 30-60 seconds on its own.\n\nThe actual script execution is instant (1 second), so the timeout problem is likely that the isolated session is waiting for the tina-reports subagent runtime to become available, or there's an issue with how toolsAllow is configured.\n\nLooking at the governor message more carefully, I see the script path and responsibilities are clearly defined in Chinese, but the timeoutSeconds is set to 60 while the sessionTarget is \"isolated\". The real bottleneck appears to be the cold start overhead when the isolated session first initializes—the agent has to start up, load the model, and then execute the script, which collectively takes longer than the allocated timeout. 具現化 overhead (模型加載、工具初始化) 就已經差不多了\n\nFor the cron governor specifically, I think the issue is that it's trying to do too much monitoring work when it's only designed to run briefly. Since it's already configured for 60 seconds, I should increase the timeout to 90 seconds to give it breathing room, and consider reducing how often it runs since the governor state file is mostly used by other jobs that read from it.\n\nLet me trace through the governor's logic more carefully. It reads the state file, makes some decisions, and writes it back. The script itself is simple, but I'm noticing the Gateway health check at port 18789 is returning False, which might be causing the script to hang or timeout on that request. That's not the actual bottleneck since the script still finishes. Looking at the logs, there's a clear pattern: the Tina晨間宏觀快報 job ran at 08:00 and succeeded, but the subsequent 08:30 and 09:00 jobs timed out after 60 seconds despite having similar or shorter scripts. The issue appears to be that when multiple jobs trigger in quick succession, the system gets backed up and later jobs exceed their time limits.\n\nThe root cause seems to be session contention—when tina-reports tries to launch isolated sessions for multiple cron jobs simultaneously, it can't handle them all at once, so jobs end up waiting in a queue and eventually timing out. Rather than continuing to increase timeouts, I should either reduce the frequency of the cron governor job or accept that some jobs will fail during peak activity periods. The cron governor runs on a 5-minute interval, but it's competing for the same tina-reports isolated session slot that all the other scheduled jobs need. Between 8:00 and 10:00 alone there are 5 jobs queued up, which means the governor is adding unnecessary congestion. Since it only writes a state file that other jobs read on demand, I could safely reduce its frequency to every 30 minutes or remove it entirely during peak hours.\n\nLooking at the actual script execution time versus the 60-second timeout is revealing—the script itself runs in about 1 second with a cold Python start, so the 60-second window is extremely generous. The fact that it's timing out anyway suggests the bottleneck isn't script execution but rather session initialization or startup overhead. The governor state file shows it's not actually preventing any jobs, so the governor isn't solving a real problem right now.\n\nI'll make two changes: first, adjust the cron schedule from every 5 minutes to every 30 minutes since the state file only needs updating every 20 minutes anyway, and second, bump the timeout from 60 to 120 seconds to handle any cold-start latency. Though I'm noticing the governor itself ran successfully just now, so the timeouts might be happening specifically when multiple jobs are competing for resources at the same time.\n","thinkingSignature":"d85c9c9621c6ad235125f386ded893dd38ea8885dcdfccac9da83fc38c59ffb7"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n腳本自己跑只要 1 秒，問題是 isolated session 啟動 overhead。讓我看看 cron governor 的 actual timing 瓶頸：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_112joakxjg89_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd \"C:\\Users\\USER\\.openclaw\\workspace\\Tina_Quant_System\\stores\"; python -c \"import time; t0